<h2>Users</h2>

<p>BerliOS' target user group are small and midsized companies and
Governmental Organisations and Departments. These are in part the end users
but also sponsors of specific Open Source projects. Because all software
created via the BerliOS platform is Open Source, end users can be anyone.

<p>Target user groups are encourage through <a href="http://forum.berlios.de" 
target="_blank">discussion forums</a> and direct email
communication with the <a href="mailto:berlios-contact@mail.berlios.de"
>BerliOS Team</a>, to identify missing Open Source software components in
their particular field of endeavour. Users are then encourage to become
sponsors and through the <a href="http://sourceagency.berlios.de" 
target="_blank">SourceAgency</a> portal sponsor either existing projects or
present their own paid OS project.

<p>Another main focus will be the provision of general information about the
OSS community. Among other thinks this includes web-based documentation,
databases for software (<a href="http://sourcewell.berlios.de/"
target="_blank">SourceWell</a>), hardware and products, news and events (<a
href="http://news.berlios.de/" target="_blank">BerliOS News</a>) as well as
search engines.

<p>Furthermore, BerliOS aims to present existing Open Source solutions for 
specific fields of endeavour, these are presented and documented using the <a
href="http://sourcelines.berlios.de" target="_blank">SourceLines</a> portal.
Discussion forums (<a href="http://forum.berlios.de/" target="_blank">BerliOS
Forum</a>) support the exchange of experiences between the users of OSS
solutions. 

<p>Finally, BerliOS offers a mirror service for the Open Source Software from
all around the world. This provides fast access to OSS for German users.

